parts:
Got it — here’s a tight CSS patch that does exactly what you asked:

- adds breathing room inside the “Book a trial” block  
- removes underlines from the CTA buttons  
- makes the CTA column the **same height** as the timetable column on desktop  
- increases the gap under the `<h2>` in **both** the Timetable and Topics sections

**Where to put this:** append at the **end** of `assets/css/secondary-maths.css`. No HTML changes needed.

```css
/* === Schedule: CTA spacing, equal height, no underlines, H2 spacing === */

/* Equal-height columns (desktop) */
.section--schedule .schedule-wrap { 
  align-items: stretch; /* override any start alignment */
}
.section--schedule .schedule-card,
.section--schedule .schedule-cta { 
  height: 100%;
}

/* Space out "Book a trial" contents */
.section--schedule .schedule-cta {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  gap: clamp(10px, 1.4vw, 18px);
  padding: clamp(22px, 2.6vw, 36px); /* a touch more breathing room */
}
.section--schedule .schedule-cta .cta-title {
  margin: 0 0 clamp(6px, 0.8vw, 10px);
  line-height: 1.25;
}
.section--schedule .schedule-cta .cta-blurb {
  margin: 0;
  line-height: 1.6;
}
.section--schedule .schedule-cta .actions {
  margin: clamp(8px, 1vw, 14px) 0 clamp(6px, 1vw, 12px);
  gap: 12px 16px; /* more space between buttons */
}
.section--schedule .schedule-cta .cta-meta {
  margin-top: auto; /* pins meta to the bottom so the column breathes */
  opacity: 0.85;
}

/* Remove underline from CTA buttons in this section */
.section--schedule .btn-pill,
.section--schedule .btn-pill:link,
.section--schedule .btn-pill:visited,
.section--schedule .btn-pill:hover,
.section--schedule .btn-pill:focus {
  text-decoration: none;
}

/* Larger gap under H2 for both sections */
.section--schedule .section-title,
.section--topics .section-title {
  margin-bottom: clamp(18px, 2.6vw, 36px);
}
```

This keeps your existing styling (including light/dark behavior of the pill buttons) and only tightens layout where you flagged. If you still see any underline on the pills after this, a higher-specificity global rule may be forcing it — this local rule should win in normal cascade.
